{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514091"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:18:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:18:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12271"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12271"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.49,0.08,0.13,0.28]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4793"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115675"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4793"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12271"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97679"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"435"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7670"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7690"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19123"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43994"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49338"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115675"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-day history of sudden onset painless vision loss in her right eye. She has a medical history of hypertension for which she takes valsartan. She is a current smoker with a 20 pack year history. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 89/min, blood pressure 150/100 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. Her visual acuity is 20/40 in the right eye and 20/20 in the left eye. There is no relative afferent pupillary defect. On fundoscopic examination, spontaneous venous pulsations are absent, the retinal veins are dilated, engorged and tortuous, cotton wool spots are present with flame-shaped haemorrhages in all four quadrants, and there is mild macular oedema.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Branch retinal artery occlusion","Ischaemic central retinal vein occlusion","Branch retinal vein occlusion","Central retinal artery occlusion","Non-ischaemic central retinal vein occlusion"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has presented with painless loss of vision, which is a characteristic of all of the options, the patient is hypertensive and a smoker which is also a risk factor of all the options. The fundoscopic examination eliminates branch retinal artery occlusion, branch retinal vein occlusion and central retinal artery occlusion. Dilated retinal veins, flame-shaped haemorrhages, cotton wool spots and macular oedema are found in both ischaemic and non-ischaemic central retinal vein occlusion. The absence of afferent pupillary defect and mild loss of visual acuity makes the correct diagnosis \u003Cstrong\u003Enon-ischaemic central retinal vein occlusion (CRVO)\u003C/strong\u003E. Fundus fluorescein angiography can also help in differentiating by showing good perfusion in non-ischaemic CVRO and non-perfusion in ischaemic CVRO.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-ischaemic CRVO\u003C/strong\u003E presents with sudden, unilateral and painless loss of vision. It is associated non-profound loss of vision. Absent relative afferent pupillary defect, dilated and engorged retinal veins, dot-blot and flame-shaped haemorrhages, cotton wool spots and macular or optic disc oedema. Prognosis is generally better for non-ischaemic CRVO. Management is directed towards treating any associated macular oedema with anti-VEGF agents and monitoring for and treating any arising complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIschaemic CRVO\u003C/strong\u003E has the same presentation and similar fundoscopic examination findings but there will be severe loss of visual acuity (typically counting fingers or worse) and marked afferent pupillary defect. In cases where ischaemic CRVO is suspected but can not be confirmed clinically, fundus fluorescein angiography can help differentiate between the two types. Ischaemic CRVO tends to have worse prognosis with higher rate of secondary complications such as neovascularisation, refractory macular oedema, and worse visual outcome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranch retinal vein occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by the presence of fundoscopic findings limited to a particular area of the fundus that is drained by the occluded vessel. The fundoscopy findings will not be present throughout the fundus and visual acuity is only affected if the macular area is affected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral retinal artery occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by occlusion of the central retinal artery by either a thrombus or embolus. It is characterised by unilateral, sudden, painless and severe loss of vision can be up to no perception of light, profound afferent pupillary defect and a pale, whitish appearing retina with cloudy swelling, cherry red spot, narrowing of retinal arteries and cattle tracking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranch retinal artery occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E presents with the same symptoms as central retinal artery occlusion but the visual loss is usually variable, RAPD can be present with fundoscopic findings of cloudy white and oedematous retinal distal to the occlusion only.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-ischaemic central retinal vein occlusion presents with painless, unilateral loss of vision, no afferent pupillary defect and less severe fundoscopic findings in comparison to ischaemic central retinal vein occlusion."],"references":["Blair K, Czyz CN. Central Retinal Vein Occlusion. 2022 Oct 7. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30252241.","Jatoi SM. Retina. In: Clinical Opthalmology Text and Atlas. 6th ed. Karachi, Sindh: Paramount Books; 2020. p. 199\u2013204."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97679"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12271"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97679"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-24T22:07:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T22:10:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4793"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115675"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":